{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638832","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638832"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:59:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:59:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17740"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17740","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17740"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.74,0.1,0.06,0.1,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10454"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75863"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10454","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10454"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17740"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61376"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"10131"},{"type":"tags","id":"10214"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24408"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24411"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75863","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75863"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EHyperparathyroidism can be classified into primary, secondary or tertiary depending on the pathophysiology of the disease.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following findings is expected in primary hyperparathyroidism?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Elevated calcium and low phosphate levels","Low calcium and elevated phosphate levels","Normal calcium and elevated phosphate levels","Low calcium and low phosphate levels","Normal calcium and normal phosphate levels"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn primary hyperparathyroidism, there is excessive secretion of parathyroid hormone (PTH), usually due to a parathyroid adenoma. This leads to \u003Cstrong\u003Eelevated calcium and low phosphate levels\u003C/strong\u003E in the blood. The increased PTH causes increased renal tubular reabsorption of calcium and decreased reabsorption of phosphate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow calcium and elevated phosphate levels\u003C/strong\u003E are not typical of primary hyperparathyroidism. These findings might be seen in conditions such as hypoparathyroidism or chronic kidney disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal calcium and elevated phosphate levels\u003C/strong\u003E are not consistent with primary hyperparathyroidism. Elevated phosphate levels are more commonly associated with renal failure or hypoparathyroidism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow calcium and low phosphate levels\u003C/strong\u003E might be seen in conditions such as vitamin D deficiency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal calcium and normal phosphate levels\u003C/strong\u003E would not be expected in primary hyperparathyroidism, as the condition typically causes disturbances in these electrolytes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Primary hyperparathyroidism is characterised by elevated calcium and low phosphate levels.","The condition is often caused by a parathyroid adenoma, leading to excessive secretion of parathyroid hormone.","Increased parathyroid hormone levels result in increased renal tubular reabsorption of calcium and decreased reabsorption of phosphate."],"references":["Khan AA, Hanley DA, Rizzoli R, Bollerslev J, Young JE, Rejnmark L, Thakker R, D\u0027Amour P, Paul T, Van Uum S, Shrayyef MZ, Goltzman D, Kaiser S, Cusano NE, Bouillon R, Mosekilde L, Kung AW, Rao SD, Bhadada SK, Clarke BL, Liu J, Duh Q, Lewiecki EM, Bandeira F, Eastell R, Marcocci C, Silverberg SJ, Udelsman R, Davison KS, Potts JT Jr, Brandi ML, Bilezikian JP. Primary hyperparathyroidism: review and recommendations on evaluation, diagnosis, and management. A Canadian and international consensus. Osteoporos Int. 2017 Jan;28(1):1-19. doi: 10.1007/s00198-016-3716-2. Epub 2016 Sep 9. PMID: 27613721; PMCID: PMC5206263.","Walker MD, Silverberg SJ. Primary hyperparathyroidism. Nat Rev Endocrinol. 2018 Feb;14(2):115-125. doi: 10.1038/nrendo.2017.104. Epub 2017 Sep 8. PMID: 28885621; PMCID: PMC6037987.","Madkhali T, Alhefdhi A, Chen H, Elfenbein D. Primary hyperparathyroidism. Ulus Cerrahi Derg. 2016 Mar 1;32(1):58-66. doi: 10.5152/UCD.2015.3032. PMID: 26985167; PMCID: PMC4771429.","Pokhrel B, Leslie SW, Levine SN. Primary Hyperparathyroidism. 2024 Mar 1. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 28722924."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61376"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17740"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61376","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61376"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-01T05:08:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T05:08:33+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10454"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75863"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","lin